

This project implements a prototype wildfire detection pipeline using NASA MODIS Level 1B satellite data. The goal is to simulate onboard fire detection for a low-earth orbit satellite by identifying thermal anomalies in single-swath imagery.



The system processes MODIS HDF files and detects potential wildfire pixels using:

- Long-wave infrared (LWIR) bands (~3.9 µm, 11 µm)
- Short-wave infrared (SWIR) band (~1.6 µm)
- Radiance → brightness temperature conversion (Planck inversion)
- Contextual anomaly detection using local spatial statistics
- Multi-band thresholding to reduce false positives
- Connected-component filtering to isolate meaningful fire regions


1. Load MODIS Level 1B data (HDF format)
2. Calibrate radiance and reflectance using dataset metadata
3. Convert thermal radiance to brightness temperature (Kelvin)
4. Compute:
   - Absolute temperature thresholds
   - Thermal contrast (ΔT between bands)
   - Local anomaly detection (spatial window)
5. Validate detections using SWIR anomaly
6. Filter noise using connected component analysis


- Process single swath images (~2030 x 1354 pixels)
- Run detection across multiple consecutive swaths
- Output number of detected fire pixels per swath


This project is inspired by real-world satellite fire detection systems (e.g., NASA MODIS/VIIRS and FIRMS). It explores how onboard processing could reduce detection latency by identifying fires directly from raw imagery instead of relying on ground-based processing.



- Python
- NumPy
- SciPy (ndimage)
- PyHDF
- Matplotlib


- Detection thresholds are based on known MODIS fire detection heuristics
- Results depend heavily on calibration accuracy and scene conditions
- Most swaths contain no fires; the system is designed to reject false positives


- Add geolocation (lat/lon) to detections
- Track fire events across multiple swaths
- Integrate temporal differencing (multi-frame detection)
- Optimize for real-time / onboard processing